> Please find underneath the first draft by Will on DNS,

> The DNS system operates a centralized core of ‘Root Resolvers’ ,

Please pay attention to the terminology. There is no such thing as a
root resolver. This was probably a reference to root servers. Also,
the adjective "centralized" seems strange here.

> servers run by a set of organizations trusted by IANA

Precisely not (this is one of the darkest secrets of Intenet
governance). The root server operators existed long before ICANN, the
vast majority of them have zero relationshiop with ICANN and there is
no ICANN process to add or remove a root server.

> Top Level domains are maintained and determined by IANA,

Add "acting as a delegate of the US governement"

> nor does it offer authentication, allowing the client to know that
> they have received a correct, “authoritative”, answer to a query.

This is untrue, because of DNSSEC (which is mentioned later but
ignored in this sentence).

> the US-based registrar in charge of the .com TLD

Registry not registrar.

> At a protocol level, the ability to seize domain names is enabled by
> the lack of transparency into DNS transfers,

I do not see what is the "lack of transparency into DNS transfers".

> or any technical encoding of name ownership.

Is it a reference to alternative techniques like proving name
ownership through cryptographic signatures plus a public record, such
as Namecoin? If so, it could be explained more clearly.

> At a protocol level, the effectiveness of these attacks is made
> possible by a lack of authentication in the DNS protocol. The DNSSEC
> protocol is not widely in use, but provides an extension allowing
> the client to know that a response is ‘Authoritative’ - that it has
> been generated by the server which has technical ownership of the
> name requested.

Self contradictory sentence: either DNSSEC exists or it doesn't. If it
exists (which is the case), there *is* "authentication in the DNS
protocol".

> Even still, there are a range of downgrade attacks, where a client
> may continue to follow the resolution of an injected message without
> such a signature, since it may not know that it should expect the
> response to be signed.

Either there is a technical weakness in DNSSEC, allowing this attack,
and it must be published, to allow IETF to patch the DNSSEC protocol
(or to drop it), or this is pure FUD (I have no idea of where does
this sentence come from).

Technical note: the DNS client knows that "it should expect the
response to be signed" through the DS (Delegation Signed)
records. When there is really no DS, the client knows it through
"secure denial of existence", thanks to NSEC and NSEC records.


