Hi,

On Wed, Oct 07, 2015 at 02:25:32AM +0200, Niels ten Oever wrote:

> The Domain Name System (DNS), as specified in RFC 1035, acts as a core
> switchboard for the internet - associating human readable names with
> services.

This is part of what the DNS does, it's true.  But the more accurate
depiction is that this is an important but not only job of the DNS.
The DNS is also used, for instance, in various service discovery
systems.  It can also be used as a rather nice way to improve user
security by allowing use of strong cryptography without dependence on
Certificate Authorities.  

> The DNS system operates a centralized core of ‘Root
> Resolvers’ , servers run by a set of organizations trusted by IANA to
> enact the organization’s decisions by accurately communicating which
> organizations have been delegated to manage registration under each
> Top Level Domain (TLD).

Apart from the corrections Stephane sent, I think it's important to
recognise that the DNS is not at all centralized.  The DNS is arguably
the most successful distributed database system ever built or
operated.  It is decentralized in two ways.  First, the authority in
the system is decentralized.  When you get a domain name delegated to
you, nothing about your operation of that is thereafter controlled (in
a technical sense) _except_ the delegation.  It's true your parent can
remove the delegation, but that's all they can do.  Second, it's also
decentralized in operation, by virtue of caches theoretically governed
by the Time To Live setting established by the zone operator.  It's
really radically decentralized.

It's also worth noting tht the root servers are the root servers
because they're the ones everyone uses.  You can change this on your
own resolver, if you want, by changing the root.hints file you use.
Of course, if people start using various different roots, and they're
not operating a single namespace, then we no longer have one Internet,
but multiple.  That's a risk of "multiple roots".

> Top Level domains are maintained and
> determined by IANA,

It would be nice to draw a distinction here, because this point has
caused a lot of trouble in the IANA transition this year.  ICANN has
two roles.  IANA today (historically less so) is mostly a clerical
job.  So it's strictly true that IANA places the TLDs in the root
zone, but it does so according to policy decisions made by ICANN in
its policy-making function, and not in its IANA function.

> and have evolved to encompass several classes of
> services. Some, like ‘.Com’ and ‘.Net’, provide a common space for
> expression of ideas, though their policies are enacted through US
> based countries.

The basic idea that gTLDs have any particular function is fetching but
no longer really true.  I don't know what a "US-based country" is, but
maybe that means "company".  It's true that many of the organizations
operating gTLDs are US-based, but not all.  For instance, Afilias
operates info and is incorporated in Ireland.

> has been recently expanded with the addition of “generic TLDs”, name

The addition of gTLDs is not a recent expansion: that's what com and
net are too.  Perhaps "recently expanded with additional generic TLDs".

> spaces with accompanying regulations aimed to promote expression
> around specific topics, for instance ‘.travel’ and ‘.ninja’.

No, the ones that have specific topics are sometimes called "sponsored
TLDs", but the ICANN-level policy difference is at best minimal.  The
operator of any domain can make policies about what may be registered
in it, and that's how the new scope-limited gTLDs are working: they
adopt rules about who may register or what those registrations may be
used for.  Many of the new gTLDs have no different policies than com
or net or org.

> intermediary parties, nor does it offer authentication, allowing the
> client to know that they have received a correct, “authoritative”,
> answer to a query.

Authentication is offered by DNSSEC, which is now enjoying some modest
deployment success, so that seems not too relevant.

> harm to freedom of expression as the DNS protocol has become one of
> the central mechanisms used to block access to websites - limiting

I think I'd say, "interference with the operation of the DNS has
become one of the …".

> Removal of records
> - -----
> There have been a number of cases where the records for a domain are
> removed from the name system due to real-world events. Examples of
> this removal include ‘seizure’ of names of illegally operating
> gambling operations by the United States ICE unit by compelling the
> US-based registrar in charge of the .com TLD to hand ownership of
> those domains over to the government. The same technique has been
> notably used by Libya to remove sites in violation of “our Country’s
> Law and Morality [which] do not allow any kind of pornography or its
> promotion.”

The DNS mechanism here is simply the ability to remove a delegation.
That is the sole technical function that is invoked, and it's an
administrative decision (i.e. actually a policy decision) imposed by
the technical means of removal of the delegation.  In the presence of
DNSSEC, the delegation cannot be undetectably blocked by a third
party.  While it is true that detectably blocking something can
suppress speech, it does so in the same way that redaction via black
lines over text does: the reader can tell.  

> At a protocol level, the ability to seize domain names is enabled by
> the lack of transparency into DNS transfers, or any technical encoding
> of name ownership.

This is external to the DNS, but it's not the case that there is no
such transparency.  That's what whois gets you.  The whois (and we
hope its replacement by RDAP) provides the view you're looking for.

> Name ownership is purely a policy decision of
> registrars.

Yes.

> At the national level, there are additional considerations. The most
> notable is the interactions between DNS distortion and internet
> routing. A study on collateral damage showed that the restrictions
> imposed by China on DNS responses in its network also affected the
> availability of sites to users in Germany, since some fraction of
> requests would transit through the Chinese network, even though none
> of the participants were located there.

I think this part is conflating issues and doesn't belong here.

> At a protocol level, the effectiveness of these attacks is made
> possible by a lack of authentication in the DNS protocol. The DNSSEC
> protocol is not widely in use, but provides an extension allowing the
> client to know that a response is ‘Authoritative’ - that it has been
> generated by the server which has technical ownership of the name
> requested.

As I note above, DNSSEC should be reflected earlier.  Moreover, one
can hardly claim a weakness on the grounds that people aren't using
the technology available.

> Even still, there are a range of downgrade attacks, where a
> client may continue to follow the resolution of an injected message
> without such a signature, since it may not know that it should expect
> the response to be signed.

If it does not know that, it hasn't performed validation.  It is never
possible under DNSSEC not to know that the response should be signed
unless one is not validating or the name is not properly signed.

> This is effective because of the DNS protocol’s decision to provide
> whatever answer it receives first, and stop listening for subsequent
> answers, and enabled by the lack of authentication or encryption in
> the protocol.

No, injection also won't work in the face of DNSSEC, either.

Best regards,

A

