>>> possible by a lack of authentication in the DNS protocol. The
>>> DNSSEC protocol is not widely in use, but provides an extension
>>> allowing the client to know that a response is =E2=80=98Authoritative=
=E2=80=99 -
>>> that it has been generated by the server which has technical
>>> ownership of the name requested.
>>
>> Self contradictory sentence: either DNSSEC exists or it doesn't. If
>> it exists (which is the case), there *is* "authentication in the
>> DNS protocol".
>>
>
> +1. Let's make a real clear differentiation here between what is often
> implemented and what is in the protocol. I think here were should
> solely focus on the protocol.
>

If the focus is solely on the current protocol then it would seem there
is no use to go into any of the social or political flaws in the current
root server or name server structure and organization. I would posit
that the motivations behind the creation of RFC 4033 are very relevant
to this discussion. A simple enumeration of the current flaws or
benefits within these documents would ignore the rich history of the
IETF responding to perceived flaws that have, or will lead to human
rights violations. I am sure there is far more context to be found in
the archive of the 4033 email list that may directly talk to the
incidents that inspired its creation, but the first draft included a
threat model section that exposes some of context.

"Threat Model

   The Domain Name System (DNS) protocol has been the target of several
   well-publicized attacks since it's creation.  These attacks are
   centered on altering DNS traffic in transit, or sending erroneous
   referral messages to caching servers (i.e. "cache poisoning").   The
   result of these attacks are traffic redirection or complete "zone
   hijacking" if the malicious referral code is allowed to propagate."

The "well-publicized attacks" that spawned the creation of DNSSEC hint
at how wide scale human-rights abuses have, and should, be taken into
consideration in the creation and revision of Internet protocols. I
think the history of protocols that have changed, possibly because of
human rights concerns, are as important as their current possible
ability to harm/strengthen human rights because it provides us concrete
protocol issues that have been addressed in the past, and a glimpse at
how protocol level changes can be made to directly respond to flawed
social or political structures and abuses.

>>> Even still, there are a range of downgrade attacks, where a
>>> client may continue to follow the resolution of an injected
>>> message without such a signature, since it may not know that it
>>> should expect the response to be signed.
>>
>> Either there is a technical weakness in DNSSEC, allowing this
>> attack, and it must be published, to allow IETF to patch the DNSSEC
>> protocol (or to drop it), or this is pure FUD (I have no idea of
>> where does this sentence come from).
>>
>> Technical note: the DNS client knows that "it should expect the
>> response to be signed" through the DS (Delegation Signed) records.
>> When there is really no DS, the client knows it through "secure
>> denial of existence", thanks to NSEC and NSEC records.
>>
