Good stuff.

I'm not sure end-user is the right term but I do think there's
a valuable thing in your draft. I hope you persevere with it.

More or less random comments, for none of which I have an
answer to suggest, sorry.

- I don't know how a routing person could use this as a guide
for how to act - perhaps this is really an application layer
concept, or maybe there's a good generalisation that could be
made, I'm not sure. But considering that seems like a thing
that ought be done. (You may have done it, but that's not
visible in the draft.)
- If end-users like something that's not really good for them
(e.g. handing over all their personal information to a few
mega-companies) then are we supposed to prioritise things based
on how they behave or how we think they ought behave? (Or even
on how we think we ought behave..)
- The set of identifiable parties doesn't only include those
who benefit from our standards, but also those who lose, e.g.
hopefully criminals and spooks will lose, but so will some
companies with some business models, and so will some sets
of people. That can be important when considering trade-offs
in that the delta in outcome for a losing class of persons
may be a good, or a bad, thing.
- If we achieve rough consensus on this text, are we then
saying that this newly BCP'd principle trumps rough consensus?
- "core values" - I'm not sure we have one set of those that we
all agree to, and perhaps we don't need that if we have a scheme
like rough consensus (see previous point)
- "Extensions to existing standards MUST document..." - that's
not going to happen and, I suspect, if ever reduced to concrete
steps would end up as mere pointless bureaucracy,
- The use of "MAY estimate" puzzles me - what does it mean?
- "informed consent" - I think that's a fiction and a damaging
one, being impossible and yet used to justify lots of things, at
least as mostly used.
- I'm not sure the HTTPS as a two party protocol is a good way
to look at things. Today, a web transaction often involves a user,
operating system, browser, network operator, maybe some proxies, a
data centre/hosting/cloudy provider, a web server operator, and only
then we get to what the user may perceive as being the 2nd party.
(Which party can also be a whole menagerie of entities, an inbound
proxy or load balancer, a web front-end, ...) And all of that
omits the DNS entities, the spooks listening in and probably more.
- I'm really unsure this is something on which we could reach rough
consensus, but tha's the kind of thing I think is worth finding out.
Later though.
- In the meantime, I hope this is on some agenda in Yokohama and for
discussion over some beers.

More nitty things:

- I don't think the code-regulates quote is useful, personally I
find it problematic, and all you need to say is that the code that
implements RFCs has obvious impact
- It's somehow cute that you choose 6525 as an example of harm;-)
- This really reads like something that a functioning IAB would
produce, I'm not sure what conclusion to draw from the fact that
this is being offered for discussion to a list that is not even
a formally chartered IRTF RG. Mostly, I guess that's good. But
maybe it'd be better if the IAB were emitting such drafts. (Well,
so long as the content wasn't mad of course:-)

Cheers,
S.



