Hi Mark et all,

Thanks for posting this here. I think this is a valuable place to
discuss this draft because we're working on similar issues here,
things that might eventually converge (since human rights are
individual rights), but where it's home should be, I leave it to you.

I would be more than happy to add a discussion of this draft (no
strings attached) to the agenda of the hrpc session in Yokohama.

I have some similar remarks to Stephen. There are quite some
considerations in there, but not as many guidelines as one would hope.
There are MUST, SHOULDs and MAYs in there, but not as many
descriptions of how this should be done.

Where is comes to value neutrality and objective of the IETF, you
might want to refer to RFC3935 - IETFs mission statement - which reads:

[QUOTE]

   The Internet isn't value-neutral, and neither is the IETF.  We want
   the Internet to be useful for communities that share our commitment
   to openness and fairness.  We embrace technical concepts such as
   decentralized control, edge-user empowerment and sharing of
   resources, because those concepts resonate with the core values of
   the IETF community.  These concepts have little to do with the
   technology that's possible, and much to do with the technology that
   we choose to create.

[/QUOTE]

Or perhaps to RFC1958.

Some responses to Stephen comments:


On 10/08/2015 03:00 AM, Stephen Farrell wrote:
> - If end-users like something that's not really good for them (e.g.
> handing over all their personal information to a few 
> mega-companies) then are we supposed to prioritise things based on
> how they behave or how we think they ought behave? (Or even on how
> we think we ought behave..)

Prioritize things on how we think the interests of the user are best
protected (as described in IETF standards), which they can choose to
ignore. The other way around is much harder, no?

> - The set of identifiable parties doesn't only include those who
> benefit from our standards, but also those who lose, e.g. hopefully
> criminals and spooks will lose, but so will some companies with
> some business models, and so will some sets of people. That can be
> important when considering trade-offs in that the delta in outcome
> for a losing class of persons may be a good, or a bad, thing.

+100. If one reaches a decision, all parts of the decision making
process should be made transparent. This will make future decision
making much easier as well.

> - If we achieve rough consensus on this text, are we then saying
> that this newly BCP'd principle trumps rough consensus?

Depends how these would be formulated, right? As guidelines, need for
documentation, tool in the decision making process, or preconditions
for new RFCs.

If it would be the latter, if would be a criterium for IESG review, righ
t?

But I guess it's more likely to take the form of (several of) the former
.

> - "core values" - I'm not sure we have one set of those that we all
> agree to, and perhaps we don't need that if we have a scheme like
> rough consensus (see previous point)

There definitely are values, also expressed in RFCs. Do you think that
consensus also trumps those? That would make rough consensus 'the
ultimate value / touchstone'.

> - "Extensions to existing standards MUST document..." - that's not
> going to happen and, I suspect, if ever reduced to concrete steps
> would end up as mere pointless bureaucracy, - The use of "MAY
> estimate" puzzles me - what does it mean? - "informed consent" - I
> think that's a fiction and a damaging one, being impossible and yet
> used to justify lots of things, at least as mostly used.

+100. Informed consent is inherently broken (and "I have read and
agree with the terms and conditions' is the most prevalent lie on the
Internet) as shown in several articles:

Prof. Daniel Solove's article on why consent is broken
http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2171018

Lorrie Cranor & Aleecia MacDonald article on how it would take 76
days to read privacy policies for services an average user uses
(old but gold) -
http://lorrie.cranor.org/pubs/readingPolicyCost-authorDraft.pdf


> - I'm not sure the HTTPS as a two party protocol is a good way to
> look at things. Today, a web transaction often involves a user, 
> operating system, browser, network operator, maybe some proxies, a 
> data centre/hosting/cloudy provider, a web server operator, and
> only then we get to what the user may perceive as being the 2nd
> party. (Which party can also be a whole menagerie of entities, an
> inbound proxy or load balancer, a web front-end, ...) And all of
> that omits the DNS entities, the spooks listening in and probably
> more. - I'm really unsure this is something on which we could reach
> rough consensus, but tha's the kind of thing I think is worth
> finding out. Later though.

Yes.

> - In the meantime, I hope this is on some agenda in Yokohama and
> for discussion over some beers.
> 

As said, happy to put it on the agenda of the hrpc session.


> More nitty things:
> 
> - I don't think the code-regulates quote is useful, personally I 
