On 07-Oct-15 07:12, Stephane Bortzmeyer wrote:
>  As I said, it is one of the best
> kept secrets of Internet governance. The professionals of the
> governance circus typically ignore this issue (too practical? too
> difficult?).

I am not sure it is either a secret of has always been ignored.  I
remember it being discussed as far back as the working Group on Internet
Goverance (WGIG) in 2005. The WGIG Report says the following:
> Lack of formal relationship with root server operators.
>  The root zone operators perform their functions today without a
> formal relationship with any authority.

The WGIG Background report also contains a discussion, though not as
explicit as yours. There have been other references over the years in
various Internet Governance Forum (IGF) and other discussions.

Over the years there have been many discussions in the various Internet
governance venues of the fact that root server operators are each
independent operators,  who do what they do based on their own decisions
with loose informal coordination among themselves. This notion of
informal coordination is central to much of the technical management of
the Internet.  There are those who have wanted to find a way to add
international governance to that, but up to now that has remained a non
starter. As you say, it may be too difficult.

There have also been some discussions over the years questioning whether
DNSSEC in some sense bound these root server a bit more as it removed
some of their  discretion about which records they accepted, providing a
technical measure of coordination.

I am not making a normative statement at this point about whether this
independence and the DNSSEC are helpful or not to freedom of expression
and association, but just trying to argue that is not quite as  deep and
dark a secret among the 'circus' professionals as presented.  I do agree
that getting Internet governance of the root server operators does not
seem to be a current work item - root servers are not even mentioned in
the early drafts of  WSIS+10 paper the UN General Assembly will be
approving at the end of the year.  I am also sure that many of the
participants in Internet governance know nothing about this, but it
isn't a dark secret and it has been discussed over the years.

avri







