I think there's an important aspect here that deserves highlighting; not =
only is lack of anonymity an issue, but also the privacy of the user's =
activity is extremely difficult to protect.

That's because fundamentally, you have to ask your peers for content by =
some identifier, and they can use that identifier to discover what =
you're requesting. Freenode admits as such [1]

Private Information Retrieval theoretically can avoid this, but AFAIK =
this isn't implemented in any P2P system, nor is it likely to be soon, =
due to the technical challenges (would be VERY happy to be proven wrong =
on this point).

Of course, this isn't an issue if you implicitly trust your peers; =
however, that doesn't seem a very good assumption to make for human =
rights considerations...

Cheers,

