On Wed, Oct 07, 2015 at 08:42:48AM -0700,
 Will Scott <wrs@cs.washington.edu> wrote 
 a message of 241 lines which said:

> The Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP), specified in RFC
> 3920,

No, 6120.

> a lack of protocol specification of the registration policy,

It is a feature, not a bug: every server has its own policy (from "no
registration allowed" on IETF XMPP server, to very lax).

> The XMPP specification specifies that clients are identified with a
> resource (<node@domain/home> / <node@domain/work>) to distinguish
> the conversations to specific devices. This has the side effect of
> enabling tracking of user behavior

Nothing mandates that the resource is a location, or that it is
understandable from the outide (the relevant RFC is RFC 7622, section
3.4). It is true that resources like "home" or "work" appear often in
the documentations and even in some RFC. A possible improvment would
be a privacy considerations section in the successor of RFC 7622,
warning of this risk.

> In practice, this leads to cases where text encoded outside of a
> standard english language ascii encoding will fail to render on all
> clients,

I do not see the relationship between this problem and the UTF-8
vs. UTF-16 issue.

> Some examples are failure of XMPP servers to handle non-ascii
> passwords [3],

Certainly, the users want to communicate in their own script (not
language: IETF protocols don't know languages). But it is less evident
that they want passwords in Unicode (see RFC 7613). I would say it is
a problem but a much less severe one.

> and gateways which simply strip all non-ascii from the conversation
> stream.

Gateways between protocols are notorious for mangling. It is unfair to
blame it on XMPP.

> the lack of actual implementation of the more extensible character
> set by all clients has shaped the protocol to harm the full range of
> expression users may desire.

I'm not sure I understand this sentence (UTF-16 is certainly not "more
extensible"). If I do, it makes no sense to me, since UTF-8 and UTF-16
can encode exactly the same character set (Unicode).

> The XMPP protocol specifies the standard by which communication of
> channels may be encrypted, but it does not provide visibility to
> clients of whether their communications are encrypted on each link.

This, and the fact that there is no standard end-to-end encryption,
meaning that a rogue server knows the conversation.

This could be a place to mention OTR (and to note it is poorly
integrated in XMPP).


