On Fri, Oct 09, 2015 at 11:28:37AM -0700,
 Will Scott <wrs@cs.washington.edu> wrote 
 a message of 260 lines which said:

> The second is the selective development of IP options, so that
> protocol extensions promoting assembly and expression like Mobility
> and Multicasting can fail to receive support from IP compatible
> devices.

Strong disagreement here. Not on the unfortunate state of IP options
(we agree here) but on the fact that IP mobility or multicasting
enable "assembly and expression". I fear you go to far in technical
determinism here.

IP mobility, first. Technically, it is a bad idea from the beginning,
assuming layer has to handle mobility. Actually, most of the time,
mobility is better managed by applications (Pidgin for IM, all Twitter
clients for Twitter, all email clients, rsync and BitTorrent nodes for
file transfer, mosh for ssh, etc).

Multicasting, second. Again, a bad idea from the beginning:
multicasting is only beneficial when everybody access the same content
at the very same time. Except religious ceremonies like the SuperBowl,
it is less and less common. Most interactions are not synchronous and
therefore do not depend on multicasting.

> IPv4 even encodes a defined option and specification for source
> routing of packets, where the source can specify or suggest a
> routing path, and as the message passes through those paths, the
> part of the path it has completed are removed from the path. This
> design has the potential to make it much more difficult for an
> individual router in the network to stifle speech,

You lost me here. Filtering based on the pair source<->destination is
most of the time done by a router which is close from the two
communicating machines. Source routing wouldn't help since you have no
choice of the edge routers. In countries where there is widespread IP
address filtering, there are only a few communcation points with the
outside and, again source routing would not help.

A better solution, Tor, does not depend on source routing.

> Unfortunately, many networks prevent the use of source routing,

They are absolutely right, given the security risks of source routing.

> The other major feature of the IP protocol header is that it
> specifies the protocol encapsulated in each message in an easily
> observable form, and does not encourage a design where the
> encapsulated protocol is not available to a network observer.

There is an IETF-sanctioned solution, ESP. Little deployment, I
know. But any encrypting tunnel can do the same.



