On 10/10/2015 06:53 PM, Will Scott wrote:
> Thanks for all the feedback. I'm working through updating the the
> first draft, and will drop root server discussion and will do some
> more diligence at living in our modern dnssec world.
> 
> Injection of records, as in the case of China, does seem to be one
> of the major attacks that the protocol has historically (and in
> practice continues) to be vulnerable to; despite being mitigated by
> DNSSEC.  I'd be interested in input in how that might be most
> effectively framed. Andrew seems to suggest the injection section
> is hard to justify from the protocol, and hurts the argument. Is
> there consensus that it should be dropped?
> 
> --Will
> 
> 
> On Sat, Oct 10, 2015 at 6:52 AM, Avri Doria <avri@acm.org 
> <mailto:avri@acm.org>> wrote:
> 
> 
> 
> On 07-Oct-15 07:12, Stephane Bortzmeyer wrote:
>> As I said, it is one of the best kept secrets of Internet
>> governance. The professionals of the governance circus typically
>> ignore this issue (too practical? too difficult?).
> 
> I am not sure it is either a secret of has always been ignored.  I 
> remember it being discussed as far back as the working Group on
> Internet Goverance (WGIG) in 2005. The WGIG Report says the
> following:
>> Lack of formal relationship with root server operators.  The
>> root zone operators perform their functions today without a 
>> formal relationship with any authority.
> 
> The WGIG Background report also contains a discussion, though not
> as explicit as yours. There have been other references over the
> years in various Internet Governance Forum (IGF) and other
> discussions.
> 
> Over the years there have been many discussions in the various
> Internet governance venues of the fact that root server operators
> are each independent operators,  who do what they do based on their
> own decisions with loose informal coordination among themselves.
> This notion of informal coordination is central to much of the
> technical management of the Internet.  There are those who have
> wanted to find a way to add international governance to that, but
> up to now that has remained a non starter. As you say, it may be
> too difficult.
> 
> There have also been some discussions over the years questioning
> whether DNSSEC in some sense bound these root server a bit more as
> it removed some of their  discretion about which records they
> accepted, providing a technical measure of coordination.
> 
> I am not making a normative statement at this point about whether
> this independence and the DNSSEC are helpful or not to freedom of
> expression and association, but just trying to argue that is not
> quite as  deep and dark a secret among the 'circus' professionals
> as presented.  I do agree that getting Internet governance of the
> root server operators does not seem to be a current work item -
> root servers are not even mentioned in the early drafts of  WSIS+10
> paper the UN General Assembly will be approving at the end of the
> year.  I am also sure that many of the participants in Internet
> governance know nothing about this, but it isn't a dark secret and
> it has been discussed over the years.
> 
> avri
