 Nex <lists@nex.sx> wrote 
 a message of 116 lines which said:

> In a time of heavily centralized online services, peer-to-peer is
> often seen as an alternative, more democratic, and resistant
> architecture that displaces structures of control over data and
> communications and delegates all peers equally to be responsible for
> the functioning, integrity, and security of the data.

An important point about P2P is that the typical user's daily
experience is not a pure P2P one but there is a big mandatory
centralised step, such as ThePirateBay for BitTorrent. The use of P2P
for real applications show us which features are hard to do in a fully
P2P way (here, search).


