Multicasting, second. Again, a bad idea from the beginning:<br>
multicasting is only beneficial when everybody access the same content<br>
at the very same time. Except religious ceremonies like the SuperBowl,<br>
it is less and less common. Most interactions are not synchronous and<br>
therefore do not depend on multicasting.<br>
<span class=3D""><br>
&gt; IPv4 even encodes a defined option and specification for source<br>
&gt; routing of packets, where the source can specify or suggest a<br>
&gt; routing path, and as the message passes through those paths, the<br>
&gt; part of the path it has completed are removed from the path. This<br>
&gt; design has the potential to make it much more difficult for an<br>
&gt; individual router in the network to stifle speech,<br>
<br>
</span>You lost me here. Filtering based on the pair source&lt;-&gt;destina=
tion is<br>
most of the time done by a router which is close from the two<br>
communicating machines. Source routing wouldn&#39;t help since you have no<=
br>
choice of the edge routers. In countries where there is widespread IP<br>
address filtering, there are only a few communcation points with the<br>
outside and, again source routing would not help.<br>
<br>
A better solution, Tor, does not depend on source routing.<br>
<span class=3D""><br>
&gt; Unfortunately, many networks prevent the use of source routing,<br>
<br>
</span>They are absolutely right, given the security risks of source routin=
g.<br>
<span class=3D""><br>
&gt; The other major feature of the IP protocol header is that it<br>
&gt; specifies the protocol encapsulated in each message in an easily<br>
&gt; observable form, and does not encourage a design where the<br>
&gt; encapsulated protocol is not available to a network observer.<br>
<br>
</span>There is an IETF-sanctioned solution, ESP. Little deployment, I<br>
know. But any encrypting tunnel can do the same.<br>
