On Fri, Oct 16, 2015 at 02:30:45PM +0200,
 Niels ten Oever <niels@article19.org> wrote 
 a message of 41 lines which said:

> https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-dkg-hrpc-glossary-01

> Authenticity  The act of confirming the truth of an attribute of a
>      single piece of data or entity.

I'm afraid that no technical protocol can establish the truth, which
is a difficult philosophical concept. Technical protocols can prove,
beyond a reasonable doubt, authenticity (the messages comes from the
source it mentions) and integrity (noone tampered with the message)
but it is not truth.

I can write a message "Dinosaurs never existed" and sign it with PGP,
it would not make it "the truth".

So, I suggest:

Authenticity : The fact that the data does indeed come from the source
it claims to come from. (It is strongly linked with Integrity, see below).


